03767nam a22004695i 9780300157406DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221992ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001574067 a10.12987/97803001574062doi  a(DE-B1597)625779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.93356222/eng1 aLocke, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScience as Writing /cDavid Locke. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tONE Introduction: Science and Literature -- tTWO The Problematics of Representation -- tTHREE Writing without Expression -- tFOUR The Rhetoric of Science -- tFIVE The Art of Artless Prose -- tSIX The Putative Purity of Science -- tSEVEN Writing as Reality -- tEIGHT Reading Science -- tNOTES -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor many years it has been assumed that a great gulf exists between science and the humanities, that the writings of science are simply the record of things scientists do and find and are devoid of literary features. Recently this assumption has been challenged by those who regard science and literature as companion endeavors, working side by side to describe, in their respective ways, the world of human experience. Now David Locke, a professor of literature who has also been a scientist, joins the debate, arguing that scientific language can be highly imaginative, expressive, and self-conscious and demonstrating for the first time how the major modes of literary criticism can be keys to the reading of scientific texts.Locke takes up in sequence six critical perspectives on reading. These view literary texts as: essentially a representation of the real world; an expression of its author's thoughts and feelings; an activator of response from its readers; a work of art, interesting in its purely formal properties; an artifact situated in a social milieu; or an instrument that brings the world of phenomena into being. Locke applies these perspectives to the reading of a variety of scientific texts, from works by Galileo and Darwin to writings in contemporary molecular biology and theoretical physics. Locke suggests that attention to the literary qualities of scientific discourse will aid in further opening up the literary canon and widening the practice of literary criticism, even as it sharpens science's growing interest in, and understanding of, its own mode of operation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015740640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300157406423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300157406/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles